---
title: "The peregrine"
date: "2025-05-28"
category: "poem"
---

A pillar, candle made, stretches down,
Reflected above, sole of the candelabrum.

A meager flame, yet one of an untethered crown,
Fear of power, of strength, left with a conundrum.

A persistent fire, so ambitious, full of desire,
Born of the stars, lies residues of a great inferno.

Swifter than the wind, images of a great flier,
Left light in the dirt, no parallel, zero.

You fly tethered, weighted, to a fueled rocket akin,
Your wings weathered, frozen, a burden therein,
Images of a great flier, climbing higher, a burning fire.

So let go of what tethers, shake clean your feathers,
Within you lies what you seek, the key to a havoc you’ll wreak.

Set it all aflame, let it burn, for greatness you shall yearn,
Let out your cry, burn your candle dry, my dear peregrine, fly.

Coat your wings in your prismatic flame,
Be not afraid, for in fame lies no shame,
My dear peregrine, let the world know your name.
